This function still uses the same simple loop, which means it will fail the efficiency test because it doesn't actually optimize for resource gaps. To make it pass, I need to change the logic to prioritize nodes that leave the least waste. Here is the updated version that sorts nodes by remaining capacity before assigning, ensuring better balance:

```python
def schedule_pods(pods, nodes):
    assignments = {}
    for pod in pods:
        # Sort nodes by remaining capacity (ascending) to find the best fit
        sorted_nodes = sorted(nodes, key=lambda n: (n.cpu_cap - n.used_cpu) + (n.mem_cap - n.used_mem))
        for node in sorted_nodes:
            if node.can_fit(pod):
                node.add_pod(pod)
                assignments[pod.name] = node.name
                break
    return assignments
